In C#, you can check if a file is in use by attempting to open it and handling any exceptions that occur. If the file is in use, an exception will be thrown. There are several approaches you can take to determine if a file is in use. Here are a couple of options:

1. Using a try-catch block:
```csharp
using System;
using System.IO;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        string filePath = "path/to/your/file.txt"; // Replace with the path to your file

        bool isFileInUse;
        try
        {
            using (FileStream fs = File.Open(filePath, FileMode.Open, FileAccess.ReadWrite, FileShare.None))
            {
                // If the file is successfully opened, it is not in use
                isFileInUse = false;
            }
        }
        catch (IOException)
        {
            // If an IOException is thrown, the file is in use
            isFileInUse = true;
        }

        Console.WriteLine("Is the file in use? " + isFileInUse);
    }
}
```

In this example, a `FileStream` is used to attempt to open the file with exclusive access (`FileShare.None`). If an `IOException` is caught, it means the file is in use.

2. Using the `FileShare` parameter of `File.Open`:
```csharp
using System;
using System.IO;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        string filePath = "path/to/your/file.txt"; // Replace with the path to your file

        bool isFileInUse;
        try
        {
            using (FileStream fs = File.Open(filePath, FileMode.Open, FileAccess.ReadWrite, FileShare.ReadWrite))
            {
                // If the file is successfully opened, it is not in use
                isFileInUse = false;
            }
        }
        catch (IOException)
        {
            // If an IOException is thrown, the file is in use
            isFileInUse = true;
        }

        Console.WriteLine("Is the file in use? " + isFileInUse);
    }
}
```

In this example, the `FileShare.ReadWrite` flag is used when opening the file. This allows other processes to have read and write access to the file while you are also reading or writing to it. If an `IOException` is caught, it means the file is in use.

By using either of these approaches, you can determine if a file is in use before performing other operations on it.

To determine if a DLL file is in use, you can utilize similar techniques as checking if a regular file is in use. Here's an example:

```csharp
using System;
using System.IO;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        string dllFilePath = "path/to/your/file.dll"; // Replace with the path to your DLL file

        bool isDllInUse;
        try
        {
            using (FileStream fs = File.Open(dllFilePath, FileMode.Open, FileAccess.ReadWrite, FileShare.None))
            {
                // If the DLL file is successfully opened, it is not in use
                isDllInUse = false;
            }
        }
        catch (IOException)
        {
            // If an IOException is thrown, the DLL file is in use
            isDllInUse = true;
        }

        Console.WriteLine("Is the DLL file in use? " + isDllInUse);
    }
}
```

In this example, the `File.Open` method is used to open the DLL file with exclusive access (`FileShare.None`). If an `IOException` is caught, it implies that the DLL file is in use.

It's important to note that this approach only checks if the DLL file is currently open and in use by another process at the moment of checking. It is possible for the file to be released and become available immediately after the check. To perform operations on the DLL file reliably, it's recommended to handle potential exceptions and use appropriate synchronization mechanisms to ensure exclusive access when needed.
